### Fragments

Fragments let you group multiple elements without adding extra nodes to the DOM. They solve the requirement that components must return a single root element.

---

### Basic Usage

```jsx
function Columns() {
  return (
    <>
      <td>Column 1</td>
      <td>Column 2</td>
    </>
  );
}
```

### Explicit Fragment with Key

```jsx
import { Fragment } from 'react';

function Glossary({ items }) {
  return items.map(item => (
    <Fragment key={item.id}>
      <dt>{item.term}</dt>
      <dd>{item.definition}</dd>
    </Fragment>
  ));
}
```

### Why Use Fragments?

| Approach | DOM Output |
|----------|------------|
| `<div>` wrapper | `<div><td>...</td></div>` |
| Short syntax `<>...</>` | `<td>...</td>` (no wrapper) |
| `<Fragment>` with key | No extra wrapper, supports keys |

### Without Fragment (Bad)

```jsx
// Adds unnecessary div to DOM
function Table() {
  return (
    <div>
      <td>Item</td>
      <td>Price</td>
    </div>
  );
}
```

> **Key Point:** Short syntax `<>...</>` does not support keys or attributes. Use `<Fragment>` when you need to pass a key prop inside a loop.
